properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain and warm temperatures today followed by freezing rain and ice pellets on Sunday. Total rainfall: 10-20 mm. Freezing rain: significant ice accretion possible, especially over the Fundy region and southwestern areas. Winds: gusts to 70-80 km/h in the Fundy and Tantramar Marsh region today. Widespread gusts to 50 km/h on Sunday. Locations: southern New Brunswick. Time span: early Sunday morning into Sunday evening. Remarks: Periods of freezing rain this morning will change to rain as temperatures climb well above the freezing mark this morning. Periods of rain will then continue into the overnight hours then change to freezing rain early Sunday morning then over to ice pellets for more central areas Sunday afternoon as temperatures fall rapidly during the day. For the Fundy region and southwestern areas, precipitation on Sunday is expected to fall primarily as freezing rain. Significant impacts from these changing precipitation types are likely. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Winter storm threatening Saturday night into Sunday. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A major low pressure system will affect the province of Quebec on Saturday and Sunday. Snowfall amounts in excess of 15 centimetres are expected. The snow is expected to begin Saturday morning over western and northern regions of the province, whereas central regions will see rain. On Sunday, precipitation will intensify and change to snow or ice pellets over the whole area. Freezing rain is also possible. Difficult travel conditions can be expected mainly as of Saturday evening. In addition, gusts at 60 to 80 kilometres per hour are expected over several areas on Sunday, which could cause blowing snow. There is still some uncertainty regarding the track of this system, which could impact the total amounts of snow and ice pellets. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
